hen there is still time to do something about it. For both of these poets, lyric becomes a way to imagine an apocalyptic event that would be both hopeful and new.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aApocalypse in literature. 0aEnglish poetryy17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aRenaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aApocalypse.  aImmanence.  aMarvel.  aMilton.  aPossibility.  aRevelation.  aevent.  alyric.  apoetics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823263493zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823263493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823263493/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK